## Diagnosis

The source markdown was written with a journalistic/editorial convention where **bold phrases** serve as visual "scan anchors" — short bold labels at the start of a paragraph or sentence that let a skimming reader jump to the topic they want. This is a common pattern in long-form online writing (e.g., Bloomberg, Stratechery), but it only works when the surrounding typographic system is sparse and the bold stands alone. Inside a design-system essay with its own heading hierarchy, section dividers, and typographic rhythm, those 36 bold spans:

1. **Compete with real headings** — the eye treats bold-as-label the same as an `<h3>`, so the hierarchy collapses.
2. **Inflate visual noise** — bold loses its semantic weight ("this word is genuinely important") when it appears every two sentences.
3. **Break paragraph flow** — readers who *do* read linearly get constant micro-interruptions.

The hierarchy complaint is almost certainly a knock-on effect of the same problem: the sections feel flat because the bold labels are doing fake-heading work, masking the absence of clear visual separation between actual sections.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Typographic role collision**: presentational markup (bold-as-label) imported from the source document overrides the semantic heading structure the renderer intended. The CMS stores the author's raw Markdown intent; the renderer has no policy for stripping or demoting scan-anchor bold.

**EAP-027 — Leaky source content**: user-supplied content carries its own formatting conventions into a design system that expects clean semantic input. No sanitisation layer exists between CMS storage and component render.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Sanitise bold spans at the serialiser level

The Payload rich-text field almost certainly serialises to either Lexical JSON or Slate AST. Add a transform that detects the scan-anchor pattern (bold node whose entire text content is ≤ 5 words and ends with a period or colon) and converts it to a `<span>` with a dedicated CSS class instead of `<strong>`.

**`src/payload/richtext/transformBold.ts`** *(new file)*

```typescript
import type { SerializedLexicalNode } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'

const SCAN_ANCHOR_RE = /^[A-Z][^.!?]{0,40}[.:]$/   // "Scaffolding.", "Per user.", etc.

export function isScanAnchor(node: SerializedLexicalNode): boolean {
  if (node.type !== 'text') return false
  const text = (node as any).text as string
  const wordCount = text.trim().split(/\s+/).length
  return wordCount <= 5 && SCAN_ANCHOR_RE.test(text.trim())
}

/**
 * Walk the Lexical AST and demote scan-anchor bold nodes.
 * Bold that spans a genuinely multi-word phrase is left alone.
 */
export function demoteScanAnchors(
  nodes: SerializedLexicalNode[]
): SerializedLexicalNode[] {
  return nodes.map((node) => {
    // Recurse into container nodes
    if ('children' in node && Array.isArray((node as any).children)) {
      const n = { ...node, children: demoteScanAnchors((node as any).children) }
      return n
    }

    if (
      node.type === 'text' &&
      (node as any).format & 1 /* IS_BOLD */ &&
      isScanAnchor(node)
    ) {
      // Strip bold bit, add custom format flag or leave as plain text
      // Renderer will pick this up via the className below
      return {
        ...node,
        format: ((node as any).format as number) & ~1,
        scanAnchor: true,   // custom flag for the JSX renderer
      }
    }

    return node
  })
}
```

---

### Step 2 — Apply the transform in the essay renderer

**`src/components/essay/EssayBody.tsx`** *(edit existing)*

```typescript
import { demoteScanAnchors } from '@/payload/richtext/transformBold'
import { RichText } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical/react'

interface EssayBodyProps {
  content: SerializedEditorState
}

export function EssayBody({ content }: EssayBodyProps) {
  const sanitised = {
    ...content,
    root: {
      ...content.root,
      children: demoteScanAnchors(content.root.children),
    },
  }

  return (
    <div className="essay-body">
      <RichText data={sanitised} />
    </div>
  )
}
```

---

### Step 3 — Fix the visual section hierarchy

Two independent changes:

**3a. Add an explicit section divider between `<h2>` blocks.**

**`src/components/essay/EssaySection.tsx`** *(new component)*

```typescript
interface EssaySectionProps {
  children: React.ReactNode
  isFirst?: boolean
}

export function EssaySection({ children, isFirst = false }: EssaySectionProps) {
  return (
    <section
      className={[
        'essay-section',
        !isFirst && 'border-t border-surface-subtle mt-16 pt-12',
      ]
        .filter(Boolean)
        .join(' ')}
    >
      {children}
    </section>
  )
}
```

**3b. Tighten the heading scale in your Elan typography tokens** so `h2` is visually unambiguous from running text. If you are already using a Tailwind config, check these values:

**`src/styles/essay.css`** *(edit or create)*

```css
/* ─── Essay typography ─────────────────────────────── */
.essay-body h2 {
  @apply text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight mt-16 mb-4;
  /* Ensure a clear jump from body (text-base / text-lg) */
}

.essay-body h3 {
  @apply text-lg font-medium tracking-tight mt-10 mb-3;
}

/* Genuine inline emphasis — preserve, but keep rare */
.essay-body strong {
  @apply font-semibold;          /* not font-bold — softer than headings */
}

/* ─── Scan-anchor remnants: render as lead-in label ── */
/* If you choose to keep them styled rather than strip entirely */
.essay-body [data-scan-anchor] {
  @apply font-medium text-content-secondary;
  /* NOT bold. Keeps the label feel without weight collision. */
}
```

---

### Step 4 — Prevent recurrence: Payload field validation

Add a custom Payload field validator that warns editors when bold density exceeds a threshold.

**`src/payload/fields/richTextWithBoldGuard.ts`** *(new file)*

```typescript
import type { RichTextField } from 'payload'

function countBoldNodes(nodes: any[]): number {
  return nodes.reduce((acc, node) => {
    const selfBold = node.type === 'text' && (node.format & 1) ? 1 : 0
    const childBold = node.children ? countBoldNodes(node.children) : 0
    return acc + selfBold + childBold
  }, 0)
}

export const richTextWithBoldGuard: RichTextField = {
  name: 'content',
  type: 'richText',
  validate: (value) => {
    if (!value?.root?.children) return true
    const boldCount = countBoldNodes(value.root.children)
    if (boldCount > 12) {
      return `This essay contains ${boldCount} bold spans. Convention is ≤ 12. `
           + `Consider converting scan-anchor labels to subheadings instead.`
    }
    return true
  },
}
```

---

## Principle

**Bold is a semantic signal, not a layout tool.** A design system's typographic hierarchy must own section separation — that responsibility cannot be delegated to inline `<strong>` tags in author-supplied content. When a CMS ingests user markdown, the serialisation layer is the last line of defence: transform or validate at that boundary, never at the render site, so every consumer of the content automatically benefits.

> *"Structure is the author's intent; hierarchy is the system's job."*

The fix separates those two concerns cleanly: the author's scan anchors become a low-contrast `lead-in label` class (keeping the *semantic* idea without the visual weight), and the system's `<h2>`/section divider mechanism owns the actual hierarchy.
